body:
As I explore this a bit more, I wonder if the problem isn't only the documentation, but also that the C/C++ APIs aren't as feature rich as I had hoped. For example, one can use the APIs to access the model meta data (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/include/onnxruntime/core/session/onnxruntime_cxx_api.h#L369), which is culled from here (I guess): https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/graph/model.cc#L249-L251, but there is no API method to access the graph itself (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/graph/model.cc#L253-L255).

I for one would like to be able to not only run a model, but also display it. I would also like to be able to hack inside of the Session::Run method so that I could do tricks like the Deep Dream thing. More importantly, in order to convince myself that things are working properly, I want to look at the tensor at the inputs and outputs of internal layers to compare results of models run on different platforms and using different providers. I don't see any way to access this stuff with the current API. If this is something that is on the roadmap, I might be able to put some effort into exposing these functions through the API. If there is some intentional reason _not_ to expose the internals of the model, I am most interested as to why not.

While I'm not privy to the reasons they explicitly didn't expose a read-only copy of the graph in the APIs, it makes sense to me that the specific nature of the graph is an implementation detail that people calling into the library should not ever need to use. From my hacking around, if you need to dump an intermediary tensor you have two options:
* Dump it in sequentialexecutor
* Augment the onnx graph to include the intermediary tensors as graph outputs.

The latter is the preferred solution if you have a long-term need to access the intermediary values.

OK. Thanks for the feedback. The second option is something I considered. 

I am not sure what you mean by 

>  - Dump it in sequentialexecutor

The only thing I could find when searching for this was a scheduling algorithm for Apache airflow (https://airflow.apache.org/docs/apache-airflow/stable/executor/sequential.html)?

I meant https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/framework/sequential_executor.cc

which is basically the core routine which walks the graph and executes each kernel

Aha. Good to know! If it is necessary for my projects, I may end up making my own API methods to get at these functions (can't see why this should be impossible) but I guess you all aren't interested in that as a contribution...

@dmedine Well I'm not a member of their team so idk if they'll accept it as a PR (@pranavsharma can chime in here I guess); but since it's general practice to not include things in an API unless there's a clear use-case offhand I'd wouldn't expect it. 

That said, I personally would make use of such an API (especially if it's easier than adding print statements within the executor or at the end of operators themselves), so if you do decide to make an API on a fork, please do drop a link.

Cool. Sorry, I mistook you for a Microsoft person.

I guess a PR wouldn't hurt anyone. They can always say 'no' if they don't want it.

> While I'm not privy to the reasons they explicitly didn't expose a read-only copy of the graph in the APIs, it makes sense to me that the specific nature of the graph is an implementation detail that people calling into the library should not ever need to use. From my hacking around, if you need to dump an intermediary tensor you have two options:
> 
> * Dump it in sequentialexecutor
> * Augment the onnx graph to include the intermediary tensors as graph outputs.
> 
> The latter is the preferred solution if you have a long-term need to access the intermediary values.

Just wanted to mention an existing facility for dumping tensors intended for debug purposes:
https://www.onnxruntime.ai/docs/how-to/build.html#debugnodeinputsoutputs
You may have come across it already if you tried the first option.
Also hopes that the recently opened wiki will help https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/wiki

Please note that the C++ APIs are merely RAII wrappers over the C APIs. It makes little sense to duplicate the documentation of the individual APIs in both C++ and C header files. Please consult the C header onnxruntime_c_api.h for the most authoritative documentation when using a certain feature exposed by these APIs.
@dmedine We have recently published improved C/C++ API documentation here: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/c. Does this help with your issue? Please let us know! We would welcome your feedback.

This is great! I know that a lot of people have the 'read the source, Luke' approach to their APIs, but I find the doxygen style documentation sooooo much faster to reference. 

Just one note, there is a typo in the url above. It should be: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/c/
Great, thank you for your feedback (and the typo identification) and I completely agree with you :)
